                                                                  2434 1451
  This evaluation provides a complete representation of the       2434 1451
nuclear data needed for transport, damage, heating,               2434 1451
radioactivity, and shielding applications over the incident       2434 1451
neutron energy range from 1.0E-11 to 150 MeV.  The discussion     2434 1451
here is divided into the region below and above 20 MeV.           2434 1451
                                                                  2434 1451
INCIDENT NEUTRON ENERGIES < 20 MeV                                2434 1451
                                                                  2434 1451
  Below 20 MeV the evaluation is based completely on the ENDF/B-  2434 1451
VI.5 (Release 2) evaluation by D. Hetrick, D. Larson, N. Larson,  2434 1451
and C. Y. Fu.                                                     2434 1451
                                                                  2434 1451
INCIDENT NEUTRON ENERGIES > 20 MeV                                2434 1451
                                                                  2434 1451
  The ENDF/B-VI Release 2 evaluation extends to 20 MeV and        2434 1451
includes cross sections and energy-angle data for all             2434 1451
significant reactions.  The present evaluation utilizes a more    2434 1451
compact composite reaction spectrum representation above 20 MeV   2434 1451
in order to reduce the length of the file. No essential data for  2434 1451
applications is lost with this representation.                    2434 1451
  The evaluation above 20 MeV utilizes MF=6, MT=5 to represent    2434 1451
all reaction data.  Production cross sections and emission        2434 1451
spectra are given for neutrons, protons, deuterons, tritons,      2434 1451
alpha particles, gamma rays, and all residual nuclides produced   2434 1451
(A>5) in the reaction chains. To summarize, the ENDF sections     2434 1451
with non-zero data above En = 20 MeV are:                         2434 1451
                                                                  2434 1451
  MF=3 MT=  1  Total Cross Section                                2434 1451
       MT=  2  Elastic Scattering Cross Section                   2434 1451
       MT=  3  Nonelastic Cross Section                           2434 1451
       MT=  5  Sum of Binary (n,n') and (n,x) Reactions           2434 1451
                                                                  2434 1451
  MF=4 MT=  2  Elastic Angular Distributions                      2434 1451
                                                                  2434 1451
  MF=6 MT=  5  Production Cross Sections and Energy-Angle         2434 1451
               Distributions for Emission Neutrons, Protons,      2434 1451
               Deuterons, Tritons, and Alphas; and Angle-         2434 1451
               Integrated Spectra for Gamma Rays and Residual     2434 1451
               Nuclei That Are Stable Against Particle Emission   2434 1451
                                                                  2434 1451
  The evaluation is based on nuclear model calculations that      2434 1451
have been benchmarked to experimental data, especially for n +    2434 1451
Cr52 and p + Cr52 reactions [Ch97]. We use the GNASH code system  2434 1451
[Yo92], which utilizes Hauser-Feshbach statistical,               2434 1451
preequilibrium and direct-reaction theories. Spherical optical    2434 1451
model calculations are used to obtain particle transmission       2434 1451
coefficients for the Hauser-Feshbach calculations, as well as     2434 1451
for the elastic neutron angular distributions.                    2434 1451
  Cross sections and spectra for producing individual residual    2434 1451
nuclei are included for reactions. The energy-angle-correlations  2434 1451
for all outgoing particles are based on Kalbach systematics       2434 1451
[Ka88].                                                           2434 1451
  A model was developed to calculate the energy distributions of  2434 1451
all recoil nuclei in the GNASH calculations [Ch96]. The recoil    2434 1451
energy distributions are represented in the laboratory system in  2434 1451
MT=5, MF=6, and are given as isotropic in the lab system. All     2434 1451
other data in MT=5,MF=6 are given in the center-of-mass system.   2434 1451
This method of representation utilizes the LCT=3 option approved  2434 1451
at the November, 1996, CSEWG meeting.                             2434 1451
  Preequilibrium corrections were performed in the course of the  2434 1451
GNASH calculations using the exciton model of Kalbach [Ka77,      2434 1451
Ka85], validated by comparison with calculations using Feshbach,  2434 1451
Kerman, Koonin (FKK) theory [Ch93].  Discrete level data from     2434 1451
nuclear data sheets were matched to continuum level densities     2434 1451
using the formulation of Ignatyuk et al. [Ig75] and pairing and   2434 1451
shell parameters from the Cook [Co67] analysis. Neutron and       2434 1451
charged- particle transmission coefficients were obtained from    2434 1451
the optical potentials, as discussed below.  Gamma-ray            2434 1451
transmission coefficients were calculated using the Kopecky-Uhl   2434 1451
model [Ko90].                                                     2434 1451
                                                                  2434 1451
SOME Cr-SPECIFIC INFORMATION CONCERNING THE EVAL.                 2434 1451
                                                                  2434 1451
  The neutron total cross section was evaluated at energy grid    2434 1451
points by using the least-squares code GMA [Po81] taking account  2434 1451
of the new data measured by Dietrich et al. for natural Cr [Di97].2434 1451
The results were transformed to the Cr-53 cross section according 2434 1451
to the A*(2/3) law, i.e., by multiplying by a factor of 1.012076. 2434 1451
                                                                  2434 1451
  The neutron optical model potential derived for n + Cr-52 was   2434 1451
used for calculation of DWBA cross sections.                      2434 1451
                                                                  2434 1451
  The transmission coefficients calculated for the n + Cr-52      2434 1451
evaluation were employed for all the n + Cr-50 evaluation         2434 1451
channels, by multiplying by a factor of 1.01278, i.e., a ratio of 2434 1451
A**(2/3) between Cr-53 and Cr-52.                                 2434 1451
                                                                  2434 1451
  The Cr-52 transmission coefficients were calculated by using the2434 1451
following potentials:                                             2434 1451
                                                                  2434 1451
  For the neutron channel, the newly-searched potential for n +   2434 1451
Cr-52, as described in File 1 of the n + Cr-52 evaluation, was    2434 1451
used.                                                             2434 1451
                                                                  2434 1451
  For the proton channel, a combination of 2 potentials was used :2434 1451
                                                                  2434 1451
below 40 MeV : Becchetti-Greenlees [Be69]                         2434 1451
above 40 MeV : Madland medium energy potential [Ma88]             2434 1451
                                                                  2434 1451
  The proton reaction cross section and transmission coefficients 2434 1451
below 40 MeV were multiplied by a factor of 0.845 to make the     2434 1451
agreement with the measured proton reaction cross section [Ca96]  2434 1451
better, and also to make the connection to higher energy values   2434 1451
smoothly.                                                         2434 1451
                                                                  2434 1451
  For deuterons, the Lohr-Haeberli [Lo74] global potential was    2434 1451
used; for alpha particles the McFadden-Satchler [Mc66] potential  2434 1451
was used; and for tritons the Becchetti-Greenlees [Be71] potential2434 1451
was used.  The He-3 channel was ignored.                          2434 1451
                                                                  2434 1451
  No direct collective inelastic scattering was considered.       2434 1451
